'''Scott Griffith''' was the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of [[Zipcar]], Inc. from February 2003 until his resignation on March 15, 2013 following the acquisition of Zipcar by [[Avis Budget Group]].<ref name="zc">{{cite web|title=team: home office|url=http://www.zipcar.com/about/team|work=zipcar.com|accessdate=16 October 2010}}</ref>

Scott earned his BS in engineering from [[Carnegie Mellon University]] in 1981 and his MBA from the [[University of Chicago Booth School of Business]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=602241&privcapId=661147 | title=Zipcar, Inc. | publisher=Bloomberg BusinessWeek}}</ref>

Under Scott's leadership, Zipcar has emerged as the world's largest car sharing service.  In the fall of 2007, Scott led Zipcar<U+2019>s merger with [[Flexcar]], managing the integration of the companies' fleet, technology and membership base under the Zipcar brand and service.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2003984391_flexcar31.html | title=Seattle's Flexcar merges with rival Zipcar | work=Seattle Times | author=Dominic Gates | date=2007-10-31}}</ref> More recently, Scott oversaw the acquisition of London-based [[Streetcar]], the UK<U+2019>s car sharing service, in an effort to expand the benefits of car-sharing throughout the UK and globally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/press_rel/2010/dec/pdf/44_10_zipcar_streetcar.pdf | title= CC CLEARS ZIPCAR/STREETCAR MERGER | work=Competition Commission | date=2010-12-22}}</ref>

For his accomplishments at Zipcar, Scott was named a Mass High Tech All-Star in 2009,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.masshightech.com/stories/2009/08/17/weekly14-Mass-High-Tech-names-2009-All-Stars-of-New-England-Innovation-Economy.html |title=Mass High Tech names 2009 All-Stars of New England Innovation Economy | author=Mass High Tech Staff | publisher=MassHighTech.com | date=2009-08-21}}</ref> selected as one of [[Huffington Post]]<U+2019>s 2010 Game-changers in transportation, and dubbed Corporate Responsibility Magazine<U+2019>s 2010 Social Entrepreneur CEO of the Year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://zipcar.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=43&item=201 | title=Zipcar Chairman and CEO Scott Griffith Selected as a CEO of the Year | date=2010-11-03 | publisher=PR Newswire}}{{verify credibility|date=January 2012}}</ref> In addition, [[BusinessWeek]] named Scott one of its <U+201C>Best Leaders of 2006,<U+201D> and he was the recipient of [[Babson College]]'s ELiTE Award for entrepreneurship. Griffith has been interviewed by many news outlets, including ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[CNN]], [[CNBC]], ''[[USA Today]]'', [[Associated Press]], CBS-TV, FOX-TV, ''[[ABC World News Tonight]]'' and ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''.

Prior to [[Zipcar]], Scott held senior level positions at [[The Boeing Company]], Information America, an [[Atlanta]]-based provider of online public record information, and The Parthenon Group, a boutique business strategy and investment firm.

